article.headline: 49ers notch seventh straight victory
article.linkText: Month to remember: Charlotte finishes Feb. perfect
article.story: CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Senior Day always makes Charlotte coach Bobby Lutz mist up. This year, though, he's fending off a lump in his throat with the hope that he and his 49ers will be playing deep into March. No. 21 Charlotte closed its home schedule Saturday with its 10th straight win at Halton Arena, an 81-58 dismissal of Southern Mississippi. The victory was the seventh straight for Charlotte (21-4, 12-2), which finished a perfect February and enters the final week of Conference USA play atop the league standings. Curtis Withers led the 49ers with 25 points and 11 rebounds, teaming yet again with fellow forward Eddie Basden in a tandem act that has given Charlotte the appearance of a team poised for an NCAA Tournament run. Basden had 17 points, eight rebounds, four assists and six steals in his final appearance before the home fans. He and fellow seniors Brendan Plavich and Chris Sager were honored before the game. "I'm so happy for them and they all got the ovation they all deserved," Lutz said. "It's a fun day, but a really tough day in a lot of ways. The good thing is, we're going to keep playing. We're going to play another few weeks -- hopefully five or six more weeks." Five more weeks of play would put the 49ers at the Final Four in St. Louis, something no Charlotte squad has accomplished since 1977. In addition to Basden and Withers, Charlotte was keyed by two bench performances. Forward E.J. Drayton scored 14 points, including two 3-pointers, and had six rebounds in 19 minutes, while 7-foot backup center Martin Iti blocked six shots. The overmatched Golden Eagles (10-17, 1-14) were led by Rashaad Carruth's 22 points. Mildon Ambres had 14 points and eight rebounds, while Michael Ford led with nine rebounds. Charlotte made the game a blowout with a 14-0 run near the end of the first half. Basden hit a 3-pointer from the left wing, grabbed a ball stolen by teammate Brendan Plavich and stepped back for a long 2-pointer and then stole the ball and slammed it home on a fast break to make the lead 38-17 with 1:49 left in the half. That helped give the 49ers what Lutz called a "working margin" of 20 points at the half, and Southern Mississippi never got closer than 15 points in the second half. Withers scored 20-plus points for the third straight game. He benefited from 17 Charlotte assists, shooting 10-of-17 from the floor and making 5 of 11 free throws. "The ball was forced into me a little more tonight, and I took advantage of it," he said. At 6-foot-6, Ambres was the tallest Southern Miss player to record any significant playing time. "Southern Miss is really undersized," Lutz said. "They like to play one-on-one in the post. The fact that they don't like to double (team), we thought we could get some things inside." Southern Mississippi coach Larry Eustachy, who watched his team finish its road season winless in nine tries, was not available for comment after the game, as officials said he had to leave to catch a plane. Carruth and Ambres each shot 50 percent, but the remainder of the Southern Mississippi team was a miserable 7-of-30 from the floor. The 49ers had 11 steals on 14 Southern Miss turnovers.
